<TEXT>
lithuania on sunday became the first 
soviet republic to elect a noncommunistpresident the move was the 
latest in the baltic republics drive to secede from the soviet 
union 
lithuanian lawmakers chose vytautas landsbergis by a wide margin 
over algirdas brazauskas in the election for the presidency 
officially known as the chairmanship of the presidium of the 
lithuanian supreme soviet 
landsbergis a professor of music is the leader of the sajudis 
grassroots movement that has spearheaded lithuanias independence 
drive 
brazauskas had already begun talks on secession with the 
kremlin but sajudis felt it would not be fitting to have a 
communist president since the communists lost their majority in the 
legislature 
brazauskas also advocated a more gradual approach to secession 
whereas landsbergis wants independence proclaimed immediately 
landsbergis victory came after deputies grilled him on how he 
would oversee lithuanias transition to independence 
the vote on secession was expected later sunday and deputies 
said there was little doubt the motion to resurrect lithuanias 
1918 declaration of statehood would pass 
deputies applauded as results were announced showing landsbergis 
had won the lithuanian presidency he received 91 votes with 42 
against brazauskas got 38 votes with 95 against 
earlier this month sajudisbacked candidates won a twothirds 
majority in the first contested elections to lithuanias 141seat 
supreme soviet leaving the communists in the minority 
a vote later sunday to restore lithuanias indepedence would 
present soviet president mikhail s gorbachev with his greatest 
crisis in five years in power lithuania like the other 
independenceminded baltic states of latvia and estonia was 
forcibly annexed by the soviet union in 1940 while under red army 
occupation the parliament will be asked to reaffirm an act first 
passed on feb 16 1918 declaring the state independent 
lawmakers already have declared illegal lithuanias 
incorporation into the soviet union in 1940 under a secret 
nazisoviet pact 
lawmakers also will be asked to restore the 1938 constitution 
that was swept away by josef stalins kremlin in favor of a 
sovietstyle law 
gorbachev and other soviet officials have indicated the kremlin 
may grudgingly accept lithuanian secession at a steep price 
specifically gorbachev suggested a bill of 34 billion in hard 
currency in compensation for factories and other infrastructure 
built during a halfcentury of soviet rule lithuanians replied 
that their bill to the soviet union for decades of repression would 
be higher 
</TEXT>
