<DOCNO> AP900311-0016 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a panel of washington insiders armed with 
topsecret security clearances is conducting a major unannounced 
review of the nations espionage laws in a search for better ways 
to catch and convict spies 
recruited from the private sector by the leaders of the senate 
intelligence committee the panel members have visited the cia 
fbi pentagon and national security agency among others over the 
last nine months 
cia director william webster fbi director william sessions and 
attorney general dick thornburgh all have met with members of the 
group according to executive branch sources 
fbi and cia spokesmen confirm their agencies have offered 
information and suggestions but wont describe them a justice 
source says the department has yet to offer either formal or 
informal advice 
the panel which includes former white house cia state and 
justice officials and a politically connected baseball team owner 
is working for sens david boren dokla and william cohen 
rmaine chairman and vice chairman respectively of the 
intelligence committee 
many of the panel members already had security clearances from 
service in past administrations but sources who spoke only on 
condition of anonymity said others received new or updated 
clearances especially for this project 
we had to get some fingerprints an intelligence community 
source said 
cohen said in an interview last week that he and boren were 
motivated by the decade of the spy and a long series of 
counterintelligence failures like whitworth the walkers ed 
howard clyde lee conrad a string of people who have sold or 
been suspected of selling highly classified information costing us 
billions of dollars in technology that has been compromised not to 
mention some of our human intelligence compromised 
we want to enhance security measures without turning into a 
stalinist paranoid state cohen added 
senate sources said the panel has no chairman but executive 
branch officials said borens friend eli jacobs who owns the 
baltimore orioles baseball team has usually taken the lead 
jacobs a venture capitalist served on an arms control advisory 
group in the reagan administration still sits on defense 
department advisory committees and may once have worked for army 
counterintelligence he declined to be interviewed 
the others have far more washington experience they are former 
deputy cia director and national security agency chief bobby ray 
inman former cia director richard helms former carter white house 
counsel lloyd cutler former reagan white house counsel arthur b 
culvahouse jr former ambassador and senior state department 
official seymour weiss former xerox executive ambassador and 
middle east negotiator sol linowitz and former deputy secretary of 
state warren christopher 
columbia university law professor harold edgar an expert on the 
application of espionage statutes to leaked government information 
is helping write proposals in legislative language 
in interviews cohen and inman said greed has emerged as the 
most common motivation for spies over the last decade ideology 
they said had declined among spies even before it came unraveled 
in the communist world during the last year 
to counter that one source said the fbi has mentioned its 
longstanding desire to be able to examine tax and consumer credit 
records in intelligence investigations before theres full evidence 
of a crime authority it now has only for bank records 
if a guy goes from a vega to a jaguar in a years time 
somethings wrong cohen said 
inman refused to discuss the work of the panel but said he 
personally has begun thinking about how to use data that are now 
unavailable to counterintelligence officials he suggested that a 
computer could be given a list of people with access to secrets and 
the irs could then tell you if there was any significant change 
either a bankruptcy or a large gain but he warned against 
opening tax records merely for fishing expeditions 
inman also said polygraph tests might be shortened to focus 
narrowly on contacts with foreign agents and then administered 
randomly among those with the most sensitive jobs hes also 
weighing the idea of bounties for family members who report 
turncoat relatives 
but this is early thinking cohen said legislative proposals are 
still about two months away 
however boren and cohen already have stolen an arrow from the 
executive quiver by turning first to prominent private citizens for 
advice a standard weapon of presidents to marshal political 
support in advance 
cohen is frank to admit that its always resisted from the 
executive branch whenever we start talking about changes so you 
have to have backup 
in the government each spy arrest is at once a success for 
those who caught the traitor a failure for those who were fooled 
in the first place so too the borencohen advisers have divided 
the intelligence community 
at the most cynical one intelligence official pointed out that 
the leadership of the senate committee rotates regularly and said 
this is an effort to produce a legislative monument to the tenure 
of boren and cohen 
another executive branch official citing the record string of 
spy convictions in the 1980s said our big counterintelligence 
problem is not new legislation but new values in society so people 
wont be so willing to sell out their country 
but an intelligence community official praised the panel for 
tackling tough questions and he added when you consider who 
they are and the demands on their time im impressed by the amount 
of time they put in 
further the philosophical range on the panel is broad if 
they can come up with some consensus maybe we can get some problems 
looked at seriously without arousing civil liberties concerns 
</TEXT>
