<TEXT>
at least onequarter of conservative party 
lawmakers surveyed believe prime minister margaret thatcher should 
resign before the next election according to polls published 
sunday in three newspapers 
the surveys appeared in the sunday times of london the 
independent on sunday and the mail on sunday they were the latest 
signs of growing discontent with mrs thatcher and her threeterm 
government 
the sunday times said it questioned 100 conservative members of 
parliament and that 10 said mrs thatcher should resign now 
eighteen believe she should step down just before the next 
election which must be held by mid1992 
the newspaper said 59 lawmakers responded that mrs thatcher 
should remain in office until after the election the remaining 13 
believe it is up to her to decide when to leave politics 
of the 650 members in the house of commons 374 belong to the 
governing conservative party all three newspapers said they 
questioned lawmakers from all factions of the party 
the polls capped a week of national protests against a new 
system of taxation under which each adult in a local district must 
pay the same amount for municipal services the new community 
charge does not take into account a persons income and 
community charges vary widely depending on the level of services 
offered in a local district 
the protests turned violent at times and sent jitters through 
the financial community the result was a 2cent drop in the value 
of the british pound and lower share prices on the london stock 
exchange 
opposition to the tax along with rising inflation and 15 
percent mortgage interest rates has helped put the opposition 
