<TEXT>
president patricio aylwin is a veteran 
and savvy politican who broke with gen augusto pinochet and helped 
lead the movement that voted the rightwing leader out of office 
aylwin a 71yearold lawyer who took office sunday often says 
he lacks a leaders personality in fact the tall and lanky 
politician with sloping posture and a plaintive voice is fond of 
saying he is not presidential 
but his long career in politics belies that selfportrait 
he has been president of the senate seven times president of 
his centrist christian democratic party and in the 1960s he 
presided over the un general assembly during that time he became 
known as a persuasive negotiator who believes in compromise but who 
also can stick to his principles when pushed 
aylwin is the son of a supreme court chief justice he was born 
nov 26 1918 in san bernardo then a rural community just south 
of santiago and now a bustling suburb 
as a law student aylwin joined the thenbudding socialist 
movement in chile soon afterward however he turned to the 
christian democrats partly because of his strong belief in roman 
catholicism 
in the party which is chiles largest he gained a reputation 
as a conservative and an enemy of the left he never accepted the 
label rightist however calling himself a centrist 
he explains that in latin america leftists have often said 
that social changes are legitimate and they must be carried out 
even if to do so it is necessary to break the law 
ive always rejected that because i think that breaking the 
law brings more aggravation than progress to the poor he said in 
an interview shortly before his landslide election victory in 
december the law is the protection of the weak against the 
powerful 
he also severely criticizes the right saying it is selfish 
and thinks only of protecting its economic interests 
aylwin initially supported the bloody 1973 military coup in 
which pinochet seized power and toppled an elected leftist 
government during a period of economic and political turmoil like 
many chileans he believed the armed forces would quickly return to 
the barracks after establishing order 
he became disillusioned when it became evident pinochet had no 
plans to surrender power and instead was wielding it harshly to 
repress dissent 
aylwin gradually joined the ranks of the goverments outspoken 
critics 
when pinochet called an october 1988 referendum on a proposal to 
extend his rule to 1997 aylwin emerged as leader of a broad 
coalition of centrist and leftist groups that successfully 
campaigned for the generals defeat 
to nobodys surprise he won nomination as the coalitions 
presidential candidate in dec 14 elections winning 55 percent of 
the vote his nearest challenger a former pinochet finance 
minister won just 29 percent 
during his campaign aywin promised to respect human rights and 
civil liberties and to increase spending on social programs but he 
said he plans no major changes in the countrys fairly successful 
freemarket economic program 
his election he said indicated the publics strong desire to 
recover the right to decide by themselves and their dignity 
aylwin and his wife leonor oyarzun have three adult sons and 
two daughters 
</TEXT>
