<TEXT>
the bush administration urged the soviet union 
on sunday to respect the will of the citizens of lithuania 
following the unanimous vote by the new lithuanian parliament to 
secede from the ussr 
the white house in a statement released shortly after the 
dramatic vote in vilnius called upon mikhail gorbachevs 
government to undertake immediate constructive negotiations 
with the government of the breakaway baltic republic 
the united states said it also expects the government of 
lithuania to consider the rights of its minority population 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater in a written statement 
said 
the united states has never recognized the forcible 
incorporation of the independent states of estonia latvia or 
lithuania into the ussr we have consistently supported the 
baltic peoples inalienable right to peaceful selfdetermination 
the new parliament has declared its intention to restore 
lithuanian independence the united states would urge the soviet 
government to respect the will of the citizens of lithuania as 
expressed through their freely elected representatives and expects 
the government of lithuania to consider the rights of its minority 
population 
fitzwater added the united states believes it is in the 
mutual interest of lithuania the soviet union and all csce 
countries to resolve this issue peacefully we call upon the soviet 
government to address its concerns and interests through immediate 
constructive negotiations with the government of lithuania we hope 
that all parties will continue to avoid any initiation or 
encouragement of violence 
the csce is the 35nation conference on security and cooperation 
in europe also known as the helsinki process it includes all the 
nations of europe except albania and also the united states and 
canada 
the helsinki process which produced paneuropean agreements on 
arms control and human rights is now being looked to for helping 
shape the new europe in the wake of the dramatic shifts toward 
democracy in the east bloc states 
the united states has never accepted the soviet unions 
annexation of lithuania and the other two baltic states the three 
states were forcibly annexed by the soviet union in 1940 
russia had ruled lithuania in the 19th century but lithuania 
had gained independence following world war ii 
gorbachev the soviet president and communist party chairman 
had urged the lithuanians not to secede warning that it could 
undermine his efforts to bring political and economic reforms to 
the entire soviet union 
a lithuanian diplomat said sunday that western governments are 
likely to wait to recognize lithuanias declaration of independence 
until its leaders resolve disputes with moscow and establish 
control over their country 
stasys lozoraitis charge d affaires in washington for 
lithuania said us officials had told him beforehand they want 
to see the government take over effective control before formally 
recognizing it 
all western powers are inclined to wait the lithuanian 
diplomat said but he predicted recognition could come after one 
month or two 
bush like other american presidents before him had reiterated 
the us refusal to recognize the soviet unions annexation of the 
baltic states 
in an annual proclamation last june 14 declaring baltic 
freedom day bush said 
since their forcible annexation by the soviet union in 1940 
the people of lithuania latvia and estonia have suffered political 
oppression religious persecution and repression of their national 
consciousness their cultural heritage has been denigrated and 
suppressed and russification has threatened their survival as 
distinct ethnic groups 
however half a century of repression has not broken the 
spirit of the baltic peoples today their longing and hopes for 
liberty remain strong bush said in the proclamation the 
future looks brighter today than at any other time in the baltic 
states postwar experience 
