<TEXT>
two months into their switch from 
communism to capitalism poles have more to buy with less money 
inflation and production are down and unemployment is up thats 
just as expected the planners say 
deputy premier leszek balcerowicz who devised the program said 
there were no surprises so far and his assistants in the finance 
ministry agreed 
i can see absolutely no reason why we should change our 
policy marek dabrowski undersecretary of finance told the 
government newspaper rzeczpospolita 
on jan 1 the solidarityled government put an economic plan 
into effect that involved a sharp initial increase in prices 
holding down wages devaluing the currency and making it 
convertible and stopping subsidies and easy loans to state 
enterprises 
its first stage is intended to make prices realistic and bring 
inflation of 700 percent a year under control with a tight money 
policy 
in the second stage the goal is to reform the economy now 80 
percent stateowned this would be accomplished by forcing 
inefficient companies to shape up or close selling state concerns 
to private owners breaking up monopolies and removing barriers to 
free enterprise 
when the plan took effect coal prices rose 600 percent 
overnight electricity 400 percent gasoline 200 percent and food 
100 percent to 200 percent 
costs of food manufactured goods and services continued to 
climb until late january as the higher prices of energy and raw 
materials were passed on 
figures for january showed average prices up nearly 79 percent 
from december 
communist governments had raised prices but none was as 
successful in holding down wages families had to adjust instantly 
to what the government statistics office said was a 43 percent 
decline in real incomes in january 
by the programs third week a fundamental change became 
evident prices reached levels at which consumers were unable or 
unwilling to buy goods 
suddenly there were no more lines at gas stations getting a 
table in a restaurant was easy and international telephone lines 
were open more frequently 
furniture stores empty before filled with merchandise butcher 
shops were full of sausages and a bicycle could be bought without 
waiting weeks 
stores cut back orders because of full inventories producers 
became desperate for cash 
there were no more subsidies or government bailouts and the new 
loan rates were too high producers and manufacturers started to 
bypass the middleman and sell directly to the public 
trucks loaded with meat eggs butter sugar shoes clothes 
plumbing supplies tvs and other products now park outside stores 
and markets 
after decades of rudeness from employees of state stores 
consumers welcome the competition for their trade 
i prefer to buy here because i can at least choose and 
complain if i dont like a piece said krystyna wilczyk shopping 
at a meat truck outside the hala mirowska market 
partly in response to low prices on the trucks food stores 
began cutting prices the price of an egg had risen to the 
equivalent of 6 cents but soon fell to 3 cents 
many people still prefer the trucks even if its not that 
much cheaper anymore at least you know its fresh jolanta 
budzak said outside the hala mirowska market 
some stores are having sales a western phenomenon new to 
poland a major department store introduced another novelty 
letting customers pay in installments 
inflation is dropping from its peak in late january wojciech 
misiag another undersecretary of finance told reporters march 2 
that prices rose only about 1 percent a week in february and 
similar figures were expected for march 
deputy premier balcerowicz wrote cautiously in midfebruary 
we are relatively close to the goal of suppressing inflation but 
it is too early for fanfares it is necessary to keep the harsh 
rules in force 
tight money and slow sales have squeezed manufacturers unsold 
merchandise is backing up in their warehouses 
government figures indicate production fell in january and 
february the slowdown is being reflected in worker layoffs 
unemployment was virtually unknown under communist rule but 
55000 workers were registered as jobless in january and more than 
152000 in february 
benefits for 400000 unemployed were budgeted under the new 
program but the government now says the number may surpass 17 
million in a work force of about 18 million 
lowered production has been criticized but manufacturers and 
farmers say they cannot maintain output without lowercost loans 
although the government says easing up now would invite renewed 
inflation balcerowicz said in a recent interview while some 
recession was inevitable and we expected it we must defend 
ourselves from a really deep recession 
another criticism voiced by solidarity leader lech walesa is 
that balcerowicz has been too slow in converting the economy to 
private ownership legislation to accomplish the conversion has 
been written and will go to parliament soon 
the government has devalued the zloty by 38 percent to 9500 to 
the dollar and the national bank proclaimed full convertibility 
jan 2 supported by a 1 billion loan from western countries 
for decades the real value of the of the zloty was onefourth 
the official rate 
traders have accepted the level and no black market has emerged 
to sell the polish currency more cheaply the national bank said it 
had not used any of the 1 billion fund because the market remained 
in balance 
our guess was perfect balcerowicz said success in this 
respect was extremely important for the whole economic program 
including prices because a stable exchange rate means prices 
of imported goods do not go up 
</TEXT>
