<TEXT>
as the paper industry celebrates its tricentennial this week it 
returns to the lessons of william rittenhouse americas first 
paper maker and in essence the first recycler to set its 
strategy for a new era 
rittenhouse traveled the globe 300 years ago scrounging for used 
rags to haul back to his mill on the banks of the wissahickson 
creek outside philadelphia laboriously he beat the old rags into 
pulp and fashioned the nations first sheets of paper 
with his small mill rittenhouse planted the seed that has grown 
into the nations 10th largest manufacturing industry producing 
112 billion worth of products last year ranging from puzzles and 
postage stamps to shoe boxes and home insulation 
but as the nations 6400 paper plants and mills churn out 76 
million tons of paper and paperboard products annually the 
industry is pressured by a nation bent on recycling 
just as the electronic age two decades ago threatened to dwindle 
the need for paper some have argued that recycling will 
drastically limit the markets for traditional paper products 
but americas paper makers are beginning to prowl the nations 
dumpsters for discarded paper to recycle into new products much as 
rittenhouse searched for old rags to recycle 
we see recycling as a big opportunity says red cavaney 
president of the american paper institute the trade association 
for makers of pulp paper and paperboard the institute kicks off a 
threeday anniversary forum on monday in new york 
in the era of the green consumer demand for products made 
of waste paper is so great that by 1995 it will lead to the 
consumption of all waste paper that can be reasonably recovered 
in usable condition according to a new study by franklin 
associates ltd commissioned by the paper industry 
last month cavaney announced the industry intended to be part 
of the solid waste solution and was setting a goal of 40 
percent paper recycling by 1995 also by that year the us paper 
industry expects to use waste paper for 30 percent of its raw 
material in the production of new paper and paperboard 
with total paper use expected to be just over 100 million tons 
by 1995 that would represent a recycling goal of about 40 million 
tons according to figures supplied by the institute 
already for example the insides of cereal boxes are last 
years recycled newspapers cardboard boxes containing televisions 
and vcrs are recycled waste paper and before the decade is out 
the drywall in peoples homes could be yesterdays disposable 
diapers 
cavaney is counting on such innovations to meet the latest 
environmental challenges and carry the industry into the next 
century 
in the 1970s the biggest threat to the industry was thought to 
be the proliferation of computers which some believed would lead 
to paperless offices 
instead the demand for paper has exploded says hugh hansen a 
former executive with weyerhaeuser paper co 
the demand for printing and writing paper used largely for 
computer printouts increased 70 percent between 1978 and 1988 
while the growth of the economy at large increased by 28 percent 
according to the american paper institute 
the proliferation of computers has actually spurred the need 
for paper rather than reduced it says hansen president of 
friends of historic rittenhousetown the rural village outside 
philadelphia which is the site of the nations first paper mill 
what seems to happen is people find more uses rather than less 
for paper 
in fact as computers cut production time to a fraction 
business executives decided they needed four or five drafts of 
documents instead of one or two says cavaney 
people still prefer to deal with paper rather than the screen 
on a computer cavaney says 
the arrival of modern facsimile machines has spawned a growth 
market in thermal paper which is expected to continue expanding 
</TEXT>
