them 
the sec initiated the investigation of drexel in 1987 after the 
firm was linked to suspicious behavior involving takeover deals 
drexel last year agreed to settle the charges by pleading guilty 
to six felonies and paying a 650 million fine drexels business 
suffered because of the charges and was further hurt by a decline 
in the junkbond market it helped create 
the parent company filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on 
feb 13 after defaulting on 100 million in shortterm loans and 
failing to obtain new credit drexel subsidiaries which are not in 
the bankruptcy case have liquidated tens of billions of dollars of 
assets since 
the request by the sec is unprecedented bankruptcy experts say 
the us bankruptcy code prohibits government agencies from sitting 
on creditor panels but an amendment permits such participation if 
the agency is acting on behalf of a person 
the sec argued in legal papers that it qualifies since the money 
it is owed by drexel is earmarked for individual investors a 
hearing on the issue is set for tuesday 
i have attempted to work out a compromise with the committee 
on this issue and we have not been able to agree sec chief 
counsel richard kirby said 
creditors have said they will go after the 500 million drexel 
already has paid the government but kirby said that shouldnt pose 
a conflict because the sec could remove itself from discussions 
about the money 
he added the sec believes theres no claim to the 500 
million creditors can seek back debt payments made up to 90 days 
before a bankruptcy filing or up to one year for payments to 
company insiders kirby said neither applies to the drexel payment 
which was made last september 
another reason for exclusion could be that the secs regulatory 
role would prove chilling to potential asset sales or 
investigations of old transactions with the sec in the room some 
participants may be reluctant to talk about relations with drexel 
our concern on the creditors committee is getting as much 
money from the estate as possible not necessarily enforcing the 
securities regulations said steven felderstein attorney for the 
